    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Happiness 101</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nancy Tilly and Robert Edwards letters commen on Jan 7 article on classes in positive psychology</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>As a retired teacher of humanities and English, I thought at first that D. T. Max's article (Jan. 7) described a good way to help students connect with meaning and a desire to do good. But it's hard to see positive psychology as entirely worthwhile if it values happiness ''at the cost of a full understanding of literature and human complexity.''</p>
        <p>Nancy Tilly</p>
        <p>Chapel Hill, N.C.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>As a retired teacher of humanities and English, I thought at first that D. T. Max's article (Jan. 7) described a good way to help students connect with meaning and a desire to do good. But it's hard to see positive psychology as entirely worthwhile if it values happiness ''at the cost of a full understanding of literature and human complexity.''</p>
        <p>Nancy Tilly</p>
        <p>Chapel Hill, N.C.</p>
        <p>Mark Linkins seems to be describing an established scientific or philosophical truth, as Max quotes him: ''It's preferable to be happy than not, even if that means the potential for creative output is diminished.'' The logic in his astonishing assumption makes a compelling argument for lobotomies.</p>
        <p>Robert Edwards</p>
        <p>Swarthmore, Pa.</p>
      </block>
